  m_Name: Lesson_TensionCompression
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::LessonSO
  lessonTitle: Tension vs. Compression
  lessonContent: 'The fundamental secret to bridge engineering lies in understanding
    two opposing forces: Tension and Compression.


    Compression is a pushing
    force that squeezes a material together. Think of stepping on an empty soda can.
    Concrete and stone are incredibly strong under compression, which is why ancient
    arch bridges have lasted thousands of years!


    Tension is a pulling force
    that stretches a material apart. Think of playing tug-of-war with a rope. Steel
    cables are fantastic at handling tension, which is why modern suspension bridges
    use steel cables to hold up the road.


    A successful bridge perfectly balances
    these two forces. If a bridge has too much tension, it snaps. If it has too much
    compression, it crushes.'
  quizQuestion: Which force is described as a "pulling" force that stretches a material
    apart?
  quizOptions:
  - Compression
  - Gravity
  - Tension
  - Friction
  correctOptionIndex: 2
  expReward: 50
